description: Old observation from my college days. Date and time are approximation. I was walking to class one morning and passed a guy who was looking down at the sidewalk. “There’s a bat!” he cried. At first I thought “now why would he care about a baseball bat?” Turns out there was a very alive, if injured bat struggling on the ground. Its wing was torn, so out of sympathy (and a bit of stupidity) I quickly picked up the bat and brought it to my dorm. No bites, thank goodness. I tried giving the bat a bit of water, which it lapped up a tiny amount, but sadly, after a couple hours it passed away. Perhaps one of my very few instances of getting up close and personal to a real live bat.

description:
My pix were taken at sunset on 24 March 2012.  The last four pix were taken by James Dillane of the same plant in daylight four days earlier, on 20 March 2012.

Observations:

per (it was clearly a per, since there were old infl present, and the plant was cespitose, with many stems in a clump.)

st 7.5 dm

lf 30 cm x 6 mm, tapered to thread-like extensive tip.

infl 18 cm, ascending panicle, many branches per node.

spikelet 4.2-6.0 mm, width 1.2 mm, florets 4-7

lower glume 1.5 mm, 1 veined.
upper glume 1.9 mm, 3 veined, veins parallel, not converging to tip.

lemma 2.0 mm, awn 0, 3 veined, veins not converging.
palea = lemma.

anthers 3, 1.1 mm before emergence, 0.9 mm after emergence when they curled a bit. 

This keys to E. curvula in Flora ID NW for California, with the only problem being the width of the leaf.

A study formerly posted at USDA reported leaf widths from 2.2 to 5.7 mm.

Weeds of California says the leaves are "mostly 3-4 mm wide".

My 6 mm measurement could well have been somewhat shorter, since it was just a measurement to the nearest mm exactly at sunset, in poor light. 

A measurement of the leaf width on another plant made on 29 August 2013 was 3 mm.
These plants referred to as cuneatus dubious.

description: I've read that the Carrizo plain is what the San Joaquin valley looked like before it was changed forever by agriculture. Well, that isn't exactly accurate. Most of what you see that makes up the grassy plain and carpets the hills is foreign grazing grass. During the rainy season (winter & spring)  the foreign grass becomes very green, and as the soil dries out in the summer & fall it turns golden, then brown. The green bunch of grass you see in the foreground of this photo is the native grass, which has largely been crowded out by the aggressive foreign grasses. The native can stay greener longer, because it evolved in this arid area, and it puts its roots down very deeply.

Black Turnstones (Arenaria melanocephala) flock together each winter on rocky areas along the immediate coast. This small sandpiper is endemic to western North America, breeding along the shoreline of western Alaska, they are found during the winter from southern Alaska to northwestern Mexico. The feathers on these individuals are particularly worn and faded. They will soon molt into their darker breeding plumage.


While they often feed among washed up seaweed and glean small invertebrates off rocks, they will occasionally flip small stones with their bills (turnstones) to get at the animals hiding beneath.

Black Oystercatchers (Haematopus bachmani) are fairly common shorebirds that are found solely along the rocky shores of western North America from the Aleutian Islands to Baja, Mexico. 

The Black Oystercatcher is the only oystercatcher (family Haematopodidae) regularly found along the west coast of the United States.

It was somewhere around this point were I decided it wasn't a good idea to continue with the hike.   I was able to call my girlfriend to get a lift out at Burnt Ranchero CG. Completely forgot to take better pictures of this pine, thoughts of a hot shower, warm bed and real food took priority, (in that order of course) but if I had to guess, possibly a jeffery pine?  I think I was at around 5000 feet, Long Canyon creek area.  Anyway, as I went up in elevation, the snow levels continued to increase.  Finally got to the CG by 2100 hrs, night hiking through snow drifts up to three feet high.  Kinda fun but not great for photo taking.  42 miles in two days, Today has been a recovery day and a marathon iNat day as well.   Good times.

Waste of a space, wasted space space wasted or possibly space waste, no matter what way you spray it, these empty lots, roadsides, abandon buildings, forgotten yards are entirely under-appreciated. I feel that many of these "waste spaces" are places of much interest. Yes, to the adventurous naturalist looking for the rare jeweled flower or the frog with 8 spots instead of 5 might have to look elsewhere than an vacant lot, but all the same there are very interesting natural history stories being told within the confines of these chain linked acreages. One that I find most interesting is the story of recolonization of living organisms into a place of once cleared of anything visibly viable. Most of these heroine species doing the hard work of reclaiming lost ground are more commonly known as weeds and yes even invasive. Still, the work of slowly bring back to life a space once void is amazing to me. Not to mention that many of those "weeds" are either edible or medicinal. Consider the Tropaeolum found in this waste space, flower & leaves are edible and same of course for the mustard or wild radish. Of course I am always excited to see a native propping its head out of the ground. Especially when I see a building torn down and cleared away only to reveal a field of poppies, yarrow, and arroyo lupines. As the story of succession continues and the plants begin to take hold other residents move in, ladybugs, aphids, ants, crickets, mice, rats, sparrows, finches, morning doves, falcons, hawks, racoons, and so on. And if that that waste space is truly wasted, then quite possibly a native oak or some other tree begins to take root. Of course more often than not the space is once again cleared and paved over to make room for the burgeoning population, but with that people might want to take another closer and longer look at that empty yard.

description: Seen this flock of 40 strong Cedar Waxwings hanging around our neighborhood for the last couple of days. In particular feeding on some cotoneaster bushes near my house (http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/37220). They literally ate every berry that was on that bush within two days. Even during a strong rainstorm they were out there taking turns flying down from perches to the bush to snag a berry then fly off letting the next bird in line grab their lunch. A berry handsome bird and an absolute treat to watch over the last couple days while drinking my coffee.

It would sometimes pause to eat a bit before scampering up a tree with the mushroom, only to shortly come back down and seek out another Boletus. In Europe, Red Squirrels "pick" a variety of fungi (mainly boletes) and store them in trees where they dry. The dried stores are then eaten through the long winter and form up to 25% of the diet. description: These guys are apparently over-running the farm I volunteer at, well, not this one anymore.  I am using a Peterson's mammal guide, 3rd edition, printed in 1980, for identification.  It was 1 dollar at a flea market.  Distribution maps may have changed since then, but based on the guide, I'd say this is a valley pocket gopher, (Thomomys bottae).  The farm staff say they are rarely seen above ground, solitary, eating a lot of the farm produce, continually close burrow holes, and I have seen the "characteristic fan shaped mounds" of dirt.  Hairless tail shorter than head and body and long, curved front claws for digging.
There may be more than one cattail species growing here. I'll have to watch as they flower.

What a relief - noticed this little bug on my bedside table and started having 'bedbug panic' - I couldn't get a good picture (really small) but with my handlens I could clearly see the chewing mouthparts of a Booklice as opposed to the sucking mouthpart of a bedbug. Apparently these guys eat the glue on book bindings which is why he was probably on my bed side table. They are harmless to humans, but really interestingly, apparently the orders of parasitic lice (headlice etc) are paraphyletic and should include Booklice to be monophyletic - its really easy to see how these guys would make the evolutionary leap from chewing on books to chewing on people!
